trans-unit.source: Creates a pretrained image classification model for frontal faces using the OpenCV Library
trans-unit.target: Creates a pretrained image classification model for frontal faces using the OpenCV Library

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> module to detect faces in images.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> module to detect faces in images.

trans-unit.source: This particular model has already been trained, and classifies images as either containing a human face in frontal view, or not.
trans-unit.target: This particular model has already been trained, and classifies images as either containing a human face in frontal view, or not.

trans-unit.source: The model is based on the <externalLink><linkText>OpenCV</linkText><linkAlternateText>Open Source Computer Vision</linkAlternateText><linkUri>http://opencv.org/</linkUri></externalLink> library.
trans-unit.target: The model is based on the <externalLink><linkText>OpenCV</linkText><linkAlternateText>Open Source Computer Vision</linkAlternateText><linkUri>http://opencv.org/</linkUri></externalLink> library.

trans-unit.source: The OpenCV Library provides a list of predefined models, each optimized to detect a particular type of object
trans-unit.target: The OpenCV Library provides a list of predefined models, each optimized to detect a particular type of object

trans-unit.source: Currently only one OpenCV image classification model is provided, but additional pre-trained models might be available in later releases.
trans-unit.target: Currently only one OpenCV image classification model is provided, but additional pre-trained models might be available in later releases.

trans-unit.source: Models based on <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> cannot be retrained.
trans-unit.target: Models based on <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> cannot be retrained.

trans-unit.source: These models are pre-trained using an open-source library, and are incompatible with other modules such as <link xlink:href="5cc7053e-aa30-450d-96c0-dae4be720977" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Train Model</link> and <link xlink:href="75fb875d-6b86-4d46-8bcc-74261ade5826" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Cross-Validate Model</link>.
trans-unit.target: These models are pre-trained using an open-source library, and are incompatible with other modules such as <link xlink:href="5cc7053e-aa30-450d-96c0-dae4be720977" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Train Model</link> and <link xlink:href="75fb875d-6b86-4d46-8bcc-74261ade5826" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Cross-Validate Model</link>.

trans-unit.source: How to Use Pre-Trained Image Classification
trans-unit.target: How to Use Pre-Trained Image Classification

trans-unit.source: Add <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> to your experiment.
trans-unit.target: Add <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui> to your experiment.

trans-unit.source: Set parameters that control how images are analyzed, using the properties in <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui>.
trans-unit.target: Set parameters that control how images are analyzed, using the properties in <ui>Pretrained Cascade Image Classification</ui>.

trans-unit.source: See the <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Options" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Options</legacyLink> section for details.
trans-unit.target: See the <legacyLink xlink:href="#bkmk_Options" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Options</legacyLink> section for details.

trans-unit.source: The model is optimized for a specific image type and has already been trained using a large dataset.
trans-unit.target: The model is optimized for a specific image type and has already been trained using a large dataset.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, all you need to do is provide a set of images as a dataset, and the module generates a score that indicates whether each image contains the target image type.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, all you need to do is provide a set of images as a dataset, and the module generates a score that indicates whether each image contains the target image type.

trans-unit.source: To do this, add the <link xlink:href="893f8c57-1d36-456d-a47b-d29ae67f5d84" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Image Reader</link> module to your experiment.
trans-unit.target: To do this, add the <link xlink:href="893f8c57-1d36-456d-a47b-d29ae67f5d84" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Image Reader</link> module to your experiment.

trans-unit.source: See the help for <link xlink:href="893f8c57-1d36-456d-a47b-d29ae67f5d84" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Image Reader</link> to ensure that the images you use meet the requirements, and for help in configuring access to the images.
trans-unit.target: See the help for <link xlink:href="893f8c57-1d36-456d-a47b-d29ae67f5d84" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Image Reader</link> to ensure that the images you use meet the requirements, and for help in configuring access to the images.

trans-unit.source: Add the <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Model</link> module to your experiment.
trans-unit.target: Add the <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Model</link> module to your experiment.

trans-unit.source: Connect the pre-trained image classifier to the lefthand input of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Module</link>, and connect your dataset of images to the right-hand input of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Module</link>.
trans-unit.target: Connect the pre-trained image classifier to the lefthand input of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Module</link>, and connect your dataset of images to the right-hand input of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Module</link>.

trans-unit.source: The output of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Model</link> includes the image name, the scored label, and the probability score for the label (either 0 or 1).
trans-unit.target: The output of <link xlink:href="401b4f92-e724-4d5a-be81-d5b0ff9bdb33" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Score Model</link> includes the image name, the scored label, and the probability score for the label (either 0 or 1).

trans-unit.source: The classifier outputs a “1” if the image is likely to show the object (a face), and “0” otherwise.
trans-unit.target: The classifier outputs a “1” if the image is likely to show the object (a face), and “0” otherwise.

trans-unit.source: The output also contains the RGB values for all color channels in the dataset, so we recommend that in your experiment you use <link xlink:href="1ec722fa-b623-4e26-a44e-a50c6d726223" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Project columns</link> to output just the result columns.
trans-unit.target: The output also contains the RGB values for all color channels in the dataset, so we recommend that in your experiment you use <link xlink:href="1ec722fa-b623-4e26-a44e-a50c6d726223" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Project columns</link> to output just the result columns.

trans-unit.source: Choose a pre-trained classifier from the list.
trans-unit.target: Choose a pre-trained classifier from the list.

trans-unit.source: Currently, only one classifier (<ui>Frontal face</ui>) is available, but more might be available in future.
trans-unit.target: Currently, only one classifier (<ui>Frontal face</ui>) is available, but more might be available in future.

trans-unit.source: Type a value that specifies how much the image size is reduced at each image scale.
trans-unit.target: Type a value that specifies how much the image size is reduced at each image scale.

trans-unit.source: In the OpenCV Library, the classifier is designed so that it can be easily “resized” in order to be able to find the objects of interest at different sizes, which is more efficient than resizing the image itself.
trans-unit.target: In the OpenCV Library, the classifier is designed so that it can be easily “resized” in order to be able to find the objects of interest at different sizes, which is more efficient than resizing the image itself.

trans-unit.source: So, to find an object of an unknown size in the image the scan procedure should be done several times at different scales.
trans-unit.target: So, to find an object of an unknown size in the image the scan procedure should be done several times at different scales.

trans-unit.source: Type a number that specifies how many neighbors each candidate rectangle should have.
trans-unit.target: Type a number that specifies how many neighbors each candidate rectangle should have.

trans-unit.source: In the OpenCV library, the classifier detects objects of different sizes in the input image.
trans-unit.target: In the OpenCV library, the classifier detects objects of different sizes in the input image.

trans-unit.source: The detected objects are returned as a list of rectangles.
trans-unit.target: The detected objects are returned as a list of rectangles.

trans-unit.source: The <newTerm>neighbors</newTerm> parameter controls how strong the image within the rectangle must be to qualify as a detected face or feature.
trans-unit.target: The <newTerm>neighbors</newTerm> parameter controls how strong the image within the rectangle must be to qualify as a detected face or feature.

trans-unit.source: For examples of how neighbors are calculated, see this article in the OpenCv Library documentation: <externalLink><linkText>Eigenfaces in OpenCV</linkText><linkUri>http://docs.opencv.org/modules/contrib/doc/facerec/facerec_tutorial.html?highlight=neighbor</linkUri></externalLink>
trans-unit.target: For examples of how neighbors are calculated, see this article in the OpenCv Library documentation: <externalLink><linkText>Eigenfaces in OpenCV</linkText><linkUri>http://docs.opencv.org/modules/contrib/doc/facerec/facerec_tutorial.html?highlight=neighbor</linkUri></externalLink>
